'''Alfred William Gallagher''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (17 May 1911 &ndash; 8 August 1990) (known as '''Bill Gallagher''') was a New Zealand farmer, inventor, manufacturing engineer, businessman and commercial fisherman. He was born in [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], New Zealand on 17 May 1911.<ref name="DNZB Gallagher">{{DNZB|Downs|Jeff |5g2|Alfred William Gallagher}}</ref>
He developed the [[electric fence]] for farmers in 1936&ndash;1937, and founded the [[Gallagher Group (New Zealand)|Gallagher Group]] to manufacture it.
His son, Sir William (Bill) Gallagher, joined the family business in the 1970s and still owns it as of 2013.<ref>{{cite news |last=Doesburg |first=Anthony |title=Gallagher Group: $200m and growing |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10803467 |accessdate=23 April 2013 |newspaper=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=4 May 2012}}</ref> Another son, John, was in the business until 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rotherham |first=Fiona |title=The genetic engineer |url= http://www.sharechat.co.nz/article/ef88c378/the-genetic-engineer.html |accessdate=23 April 2013 |newspaper=ShareChat |date=1 June 2001}}</ref>
Gallagher died from cancer in [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] in 1990 and was buried in Hamilton Park Cemetery.<ref name="DNZB Gallagher"/>
