{{Cleanup|reason=the article lacks specificity about how the program works, how players are selected for the program, and criteria for graduation|date=May 2015}} [[File:GenerationAdidas.PNG|thumb|right|200px|Generation Adidas official logo]] '''Generation Adidas''' is a joint venture between [[Major League Soccer]] and [[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer]] aimed at raising the level of young professional [[football (soccer)|soccer]] talent in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/354854/us-u-20-players-headline-2006-class|title=U.S. U-20 players headline 2006 class|author=|date=|website=ESPNFC.com}}</ref> The program, sponsored by [[Adidas]], offers professional-ready players in the U.S. developmental system not yet eligible for the [[MLS SuperDraft]] early entry, allowing MLS to compete with foreign professional clubs without comparable restrictions on player signing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ussoccerplayers.com/2010/01/mccabe-explains-generation-adidas.html|title=McCabe Explains Generation adidas|author=|date=|website=US Soccer Players}}</ref> From its establishment in 1997 to 2005, the program was sponsored by [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] and was called '''Project-40'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ussoccerplayers.com/resource_center/soccer_history/447766.html|title=US Soccer Players|author=|date=|website=www.ussoccerplayers.com}}</ref> Originally intended to improve the U.S. national team player pool, American national team eligibility is no longer required for program entry.
[[Carlos Parra]] was the first Project-40 player when he signed with the league and was allocated to the [[New York Red Bulls|New York/New Jersey MetroStars]] in 1997. Since then, the program has included players such as [[Tim Howard]], [[DaMarcus Beasley]], [[Maurice Edu]], [[Carlos Bocanegra]], [[Clint Dempsey]], [[Jozy Altidore]], [[Ben Olsen]], [[Sacha Kljestan]], [[Freddy Adu]], [[Brad Guzan]], [[Michael Bradley (soccer)|Michael Bradley]], [[Nick Rimando]], and [[Kyle Beckerman]].
Generation Adidas players do not count against the MLS senior roster and usually earn a much higher salary than the league minimum. Entering into the program automatically classifies a player as [[professional]], and thus disqualifies them from playing college soccer. As a result, Generation Adidas players are also guaranteed scholarships to continue their college education should their professional career not pan out.
From 1998 to 2000, MLS entered a team of Project-40 players, supplemented by other MLS players who did not get much playing time, into the [[USL First Division|A-League]] in the [[United Soccer Leagues|USL]].
In 2017, MLS introduced Canadian Generation Adidas players, part of a new initiative with the [[Canadian Soccer Association]]. Canadian Generation Adidas players count as domestic players on US based MLS teams.<ref>http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/01/04/mls-announces-2017-generation-adidas-class-and-senior-signings</ref>
